<section>
	<section>
	<h1>Semantics of propositional logic</h1>
	<h3>Defining properties of propositions</h3>
	</section>
	
	<section>
	<h2>Properties of propositions</h2>
	
	<ul>
		<li class="fragment">Just as in categorical logic, we can use our semantics for propositional logic to define properties of propositions.</li>
		<ul>
			<li class="fragment">Tautology: <span class="fragment">A proposition is <em>tautologous</em>, if it is impossible for it to be <em>false</em>.</span></li>	
			<li class="fragment">Contradiction: <span class="fragment">A proposition is <em>contradictory</em>, if it is impossible for it to be <em>true</em>.</span></li>	
			<li class="fragment">Equivalence: <span class="fragment">Two propositions are <em>equivalent</em>, if they are true in all the same situations and false in all the same situations.</span></li>	
			<li class="fragment">(In)consistency: <span class="fragment">Two propositions are (in)consistent if it is (im)possible for both to be true simultaneously.</span></li>	
		</ul>	
	</ul>
	</section>
	
	<section>
	<h2>Properties and truth tables</h2>
	
	<p class="fragment">We can determine what property (if any) that a particular WFF has by looking to its truth table.</p>
		<ul>
			<li class="fragment">Tautology: <span class="fragment">A proposition is <em>tautologous</em> if its column in the truth table has a T in every row.</span></li>	
			<!--<ul><li class="fragment">It is true in every possible situation.</li></ul>-->
			<li class="fragment">Contradiction: <span class="fragment">A proposition is <em>contradictory</em> if its column has an F in every row.</span></li>	
			<!--<ul><li class="fragment">It is false in every possible situation.</li></ul>-->
			<li class="fragment">Equivalence: <span class="fragment">Two propositions are <em>equivalent</em>, if their columns have the same truth value in every row.</span></li>	
			<!--<ul><li class="fragment">The two propositions agree in every possible situation.</li></ul>-->
			<li class="fragment">Consistency: <span class="fragment">Two propositions are <em>consistent</em>, if they both have a T in at least one row.</span></li>
			<ul><li class="fragment">Inconsistency means that in no row do both have a T.</li></ul>
		</ul>	
	</section>
	
	<section>
	<h2>Semantic properties</h2>
	<h4>Examples</h4>
	
	<table class="fragment" style="float: left; margin-left: 20%">
	<caption>Tautology</caption>
<thead>
<th style="text-align: center;">A</th>
<th style="text-align: center;">&#x223C;A</th>
<th style="text-align: center;">A &#x2228; &#x223C;A</th>
