<section>
	<section>
	<h1>Arguments in propositional logic</h1>
	</section>
	
	<section>
	<h2>Arguments in propositional logic</h2>
	
	<ul>
		<li class="fragment">In categorical logic, we limited our discussion to arguments that had only 1 or 2 premises.</li>
		<ul><li class="fragment">This was in part due to the methods that we had for testing the validity of arguments in categorical logic.</li></ul>
		<li class="fragment">We'll also look at various methods for testing the validity of arguments in propositional logic.</li>
		<ul><li class="fragment">Unlike categorical logic, there is no limit to the size of argument that these methods can test.</li></ul>
		<li class="fragment">But, we'll still start with simple arguments such as</li>
	</ul>
	</section>
	
	<section>
	<h2>Arguments in propositional logic</h2>
	<p>Examples</p>
	
	<ol class="fragment">
		<li>A &#x2219; B</li>
		<li>A</li>
		<hr>
		<li>B</li>
	</ol>
	
	<ol class="fragment">
		<li>A &#x2228; B</li>
		<li>&#x223C;A</li>
		<hr>
		<li>B</li>
	</ol>
	
	<ol class="fragment">
		<li>A &#x2283; B</li>
		<li>B &#x2283; C</li>
		<hr>
		<li>A &#x2283; C</li>
	</ol>
	</section>
</section>

<section>
	<section>
	<h1>Validity in propositional logic</h1>
	<h3>Assessing arguments</h3>
	</section>
	
	<section>
	<h2>Truth tables for arguments</h2>
	
	<ul>
		<li class="fragment">Arguments aren't any different from complex propositions, as far as PL is concerned.</li>
		<li class="fragment">So, we can create truth tables for arguments the same way we did for complex propositions</li>
		<li class="fragment">But we can condense them a little bit.</li>
		<li class="fragment">Leave out the columns for individual propositional variables.</li>
		<li class="fragment">Just create a column for every premise in the argument.</li>
		<li class="fragment">And finish with a column for the conclusion.</li>
		<li class="fragment">Add indicators in each column to tell what it role it plays in the argument.</li>
	</ul>
	</section>
	
	<section>
	<h2>Truth table for arguments</h2>
	<p>Example 1</p>
	<hr>
	<p></p>
	
	<ol class="fragment" style="float: left; margin-left: 20%;">
