<section>
	<section>
	<h1>Indirect truth tables</h1>
	<h3>Speeding up the process</h3>
	</section>
	
	<section>
	<h2>Indirect truth tables</h2>
	
	<ul>
		<li class="fragment">Truth tables can be somewhat time consuming.</li>
		<ul><li class="fragment">This is especially true when there are a lot of propositional variables in a complex WFF or a lot of premises in an argument.</li></ul>
		<li class="fragment">Indirect truth tables provide us with a quicker way to determine properties such as:</li>
		<ul><li class="fragment">Validity
			<li class="fragment">Contradiction</li>
			<li class="fragment">Consistency</li>
		</ul>
		<li class="fragment">If we know what property we are looking for, we only need one line of the truth table to determine whether it holds.</li>
	</ul>
	
	</section>
	
		<section>
	<h2>Indirect truth tables</h2>
	<p>Validity</p>
	
	<ul>
		<li class="fragment">If an argument is valid, then you know that it's impossible for the premises to be true without the conclusion also being true.</li>
		<li class="fragment">So, to test this, we attempt to make all the premises true, but have the conclusion be false.</li>
		<li class="fragment">If we can do this consistently, the argument is invalid.</li>
		<li class="fragment">If we run into a contradiction, it is valid.</li>
	</ul>

	
	</section>
	
	<section>
	<h2>Testing validity</h2>
	<h4>Example</h4>
	
<table class="fragment" style="float: left; margin-left: 20px;">
